# Azure transcript intake (`rough.txt`)

When the user wants to process **AZURE-PROJECTS/rough.txt** (or it is the active focus and they ask to convert / publish / file notes), do the following in order.

## 1. Read the source

- Read **AZURE-PROJECTS/rough.txt** in full. If it is empty, tell the user to paste transcript content and stop.

## 2. Classify: notes vs lab project

- **notes** (`AZURE-PROJECTS/documents/`): conceptual study material, exam topics, definitions, comparisons, admin center walkthroughs explained as learning, certification-focused summaries.
- **projects** (`AZURE-PROJECTS/documents/`): hands-on labs, step-by-step portal/CLI exercises, “create a VM”, “deploy X”, lab objectives, exercises to repeat.

If both appear, split into two files (only when clearly mixed) using distinct kebab-case filenames in `documents/`; otherwise pick the dominant purpose and use one file.

**Always** save new markdown outputs under **`AZURE-PROJECTS/documents/`** (not `notes/` or `projects/`).

## 3. Research before writing

- Use **web search** and official Microsoft Learn / Azure docs to verify names, SKUs, portal paths, CLI/PowerShell syntax, and product behavior. Transcripts go stale quickly.
- Update anything outdated in the draft so the final markdown reflects **current** Azure behavior. Note the study date in the doc (e.g. footer line: `Last reviewed: …`) when you had to change facts.

## 4. File name and title

- Derive the **filename** from the top topic: short **kebab-case** English, only letters, numbers, hyphens (e.g. `azure-resource-groups-and-tags.md`).
- Start the file with a single `#` title that matches the topic (clear for a **high school** reader: plain language, define jargon on first use).

## 4b. Introduction and table of contents (required at top of every new file)

Immediately after the `#` title, before the main lesson content:

1. **`## Introduction`** — A short section (a few sentences) that states **what this document covers**, **why it matters for Azure study or labs**, and **what the reader will be able to do or understand** when done. Use plain language.

2. **`## Table of contents`** — A **well-organized** TOC that links to **every** substantive `##` and `###` heading in the rest of the file (match the final heading text and order). Use standard Markdown local links, for example:

   ```markdown
   ## Table of contents

   - [Introduction](#introduction)
   - [First major topic](#first-major-topic)
     - [Subtopic A](#subtopic-a)
     - [Subtopic B](#subtopic-b)
   - [Second major topic](#second-major-topic)
   ```

   - Build anchor slugs the way GitHub renders them: lowercase, spaces → hyphens, strip punctuation where needed so links work.
   - Nest `###` entries under their parent `##` with two-space indent for readability.
   - Do not list “Table of contents” as an entry inside itself.

Then continue with the body sections (first real content heading after the TOC).

## 5. Markdown structure and style

- Organize the body with logical `##` / `###` headings (these must match what you listed in the TOC).
- **Main bullet points** must use task-list checkboxes with an **x** (completed style for the main ideas), one idea per line:

  ```markdown
  - [x] Main idea stated simply
  ```

- **Sub-bullets** under a main item: indent with **two spaces**, use a normal unordered list with a **hyphen** (reads as a dot in most renderers):

  ```markdown
  - [x] Main idea
    - Extra detail or example
    - Another sub-point
  ```

- Be **detailed** but **scannable**: short paragraphs, tables only when they clarify comparisons.
- End with a **Key terms** or **Quick recap** section if it helps retention.

## 6. Write the file

- Create **AZURE-PROJECTS/documents/** if missing.
- Save the new `.md` file there using the kebab-case name from step 4.

## 7. Update **AZURE-PROJECTS/README.md**

- Add **one** new list item in the matching section:
  - Lab files → under the **PROJECT** list (first `## AZURE PROJECTS` block in the current README).
  - Study notes → under the **NOTE** list (second block; same heading today—keep consistency unless the user has renamed it).
- Match existing link style:

  ```markdown
  - [ ] [Human-readable title](./documents/your-file.md)
  ```

  Use **`./documents/`** for both study notes and lab write-ups. Use **relative** paths from `README.md`.

## 8. Optional cleanup

- After a successful run, you may **clear** `rough.txt` only if the user asked to “move” or “publish” content; if unsure, leave `rough.txt` as-is.

## 9. Tone

- Explain for someone studying for **Microsoft Azure certification** without assuming prior IT depth: analogies welcome, acronyms expanded once.
